      "policy_language_bans_chokeholds_and_strangleholds": "Category: Bans Chokeholds and Strangleholds \nCity Policy: Sheriff's Department Policy Manual \nImpact on Police Violence: Does not ban chokeholds or strangleholds.",
      "duty_to_intervene": 0,
      "policy_language_duty_to_intervene": "Category: Duty to Intervene\nCity Policy: Sheriff's Department Policy Manual\nImpact on Police Violence: Sheriff's Department Policy Manual does not require officers to intervene when witnessing another officer use excessive force. Officers are, however, required to report these incidents to their supervisors. \nPolicy Language: It shall be the duty of all Sheriff’s Office personnel to conduct themselves in a professional manner at all times. Personnel shall treat people that they interact with in a courteous manner. Personnel shall not be overly aggressive or physically abusive. Personnel shall use whatever reasonable force is necessary to affect an arrest or resolve a hostile situation. The amount of force used is strictly within the sound judgment of the personnel involved. Personnel who have reasonable cause to believe that excessive force has been used on a subject shall report the incident to a supervisor. The Sheriff’s Office encourages personnel to exercise sound, prudent, and reasonable judgment when using force to affect an arrest. If Sheriff’s Office personnel should use more force than is determined to be reasonable under the circumstances, he/she may be subject to disciplinary action",
      "requires_warning_before_shooting": 1,
      "policy_language_requires_warning_before_shooting": "Category: Requires Verbal Warning Before Shooting \nCity Policy: Sheriff's Department Policy Manual \nImpact on Police Violence: Requires officers to give a verbal warning prior to shooting \nPolicy Language: IV. F 2. Personnel may use deadly force to stop a fleeing subject when he/she has probable cause to believe that the person has committed, or intends to commit, a felony involving the infliction or threatened infliction of serious bodily injury or death, and the employee reasonably believes that there is an imminent risk of serious bodily injury or death to any other person if the subject is not immediately apprehended. Under such circumstances, a verbal warning should precede the use of deadly force, where feasible.",
      "restricts_shooting_at_moving_vehicles": 0,
      "policy_language_restricts_shooting_at_moving_vehicles": "Category: Bans Shooting at Moving Vehicles\nCity Policy: Sheriff's Department Policy Manual \nImpact on Police Violence: Allows officers to shoot at moving vehicles even when the vehicle itself is considered the only threat. The <a href=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/sep/01/moving-targets-police-shootings-vehicles-the-counted> federal government, activists and even law enforcement groups have recommended that this practice be banned because it endangers lives.",
      "requires_comprehensive_reporting": 0,
      "policy_language_requires_comprehensive_reporting": "Category: Requires Comprehensive Use of Force Reporting\nCity Policy: Sheriff's Department Policy Manual\nImpact on Police Accountability: Does not require officers to report when they point a firearm at a civilian.\nPolicy Language: V. Reporting and Reviewing Individual Use of Force Incidents:\nA. Reportable Force Defined: An on- or off-duty incident wherein personnel pursuant to their official capacity use a level of force above the \"Compliance Techniques\" level of force, or any incident in which an injury or complaint of injury occurs during the course of gaining control of a subject who is actively resisting.",
      "requires_exhaust_other_means_before_shooting": 0,
      "policy_language_requires_exhaust_other_means_before_shooting": "Category: Requires Exhaust Reasonable Alternatives Before Shooting\nCity Policy: Sheriff's Department Policy Manual\nImpact on Police Accountability: Does not require officers to use reasonable alternatives before using deadly force. Instead, Department Policy allows officers to use deadly force whenever they \"reasonably\" believe there to be an imminent threat, even if reasonable alternatives such as non-lethal force could have been effectively used instead.\nPolicy Language: F. Deadly Force. Use of deadly force is justified in the following circumstances:\n1. Personnel may use deadly force to protect him/herself or others from what he/she reasonably\nbelieves would be an imminent threat of death or serious bodily injury.\n2. Personnel may use deadly force to stop a fleeing subject when he/she has probable cause to\nbelieve that the person has committed, or intends to commit, a felony involving the infliction\nor threatened infliction of serious bodily injury or death, and the employee reasonably\nbelieves that there is an imminent risk of serious bodily injury or death to any other person if\nthe subject is not immediately apprehended. Under such circumstances, a verbal warning\nshould precede the use of deadly force, where feasible.\n3. Imminent does not mean immediate or instantaneous. An imminent danger may exist even if\nthe suspect is not at that very moment pointing a weapon at someone. For example, an\nimminent danger may exist if an employee reasonably believes any of the following:\na. The person has a weapon or is attempting to access one and it is reasonable to believe\nthe person intends to use it against the employee or another.\n\nb. The person is capable of causing serious bodily injury or death without a weapon and it is\nreasonable to believe the person intends to do so.",
      "has_use_of_force_continuum": 1,
      "policy_language_has_use_of_force_continuum": "Category: Has Use of Force Continuum\nCity Policy: Sheriff's Department Policy Manual \nImpact on Police Violence: Department has a Use of Force Continuum. \nPolicy Language:IV Personnel Response Options \nA. Professional Presence: Includes display of authority as a peace officer and such non-verbal\nmeans of communication as body language, demeanor, and manner of approaching.\nB. Verbalization: Involves the direction, and commands given to the subject.\nC. Restraining and detaining: Includes personnel laying hands on a subject with the intention of\ngaining control of the subject. Examples include the use of a firm grip, escort position or\ngrappling types of techniques designed to hold a subject down by using the weight of a\npersonnel's body. Also included in this level would be the application of temporary restraining\ndevices such as handcuffs and leg restraints.\nD. Compliance Techniques: Includes joint manipulations, pressure point applications, takedown\ntype techniques and the use of impact weapons in control type configurations.\nE. Intermediate Force: Includes chemical agents such as mace and oleoresin capsicum based\nproducts; electronic immobilization devices; use of upper body control holds such as the lateral\nvascular neck restraint; the use of impact weapons in an impact mode, Law Enforcement K-9 and\nthe use of personal body weapons such as hands, feet, elbows and knees to strike a subject.\nF. Lethal Force: Includes the use of a firearm or any force that has a reasonable likelihood of\ncausing death or serious physical harm.\n1. Use of lethal force is authorized when it appears to be reasonably necessary and\ngenerally:\na. To protect personnel from death or serious bodily injury.\nb. To protect the life of other personnel who is threatened with death or serious\nbodily injury.\nc. To protect the life of a victim of a crime in which the use or threatened use of\ndeadly force is a factor.\nd. To prevent a crime in which human life is in serious jeopardy as a result of the\nuse or threatened use of deadly force.\ne. To apprehend a fleeing suspect known to have committed a crime involving the\nuse of deadly force."
