      "policy_language_requires_exhaust_other_means_before_shooting": "Category: Requires Exhaust Reasonable Alternatives Before Shooting\nCity Policy: Sheriff's Department Policy Manual\nImpact on Police Accountability: Does not require officers to use reasonable alternatives before using deadly force. Instead, Department Policy allows officers to use deadly force whenever they \"reasonably\" believe there to be an imminent threat, even if reasonable alternatives such as non-lethal force could have been effectively used instead.\nPolicy Language: III 3. USE OF FORCE \n4.e e. Justification for the use of force is limited to what is reasonably known or perceived by the officer at the time. Facts discovered after the event, no matter how compelling, cannot be\nconsidered in later determining whether the force was justified.\n6. SUMMARY The decision to use force rests with each officer. While there is no way to specify the exact amount or type of reasonable force to be applied in any situation, each officer is expected to use these guidelines to make such decisions in a professional, impartial and safe manner.\nA. AUTHORIZED DISCHARGE OF FIREARMS POLICY\nThe policy of this department is that deputies may discharge firearms when, in light of information reasonably available to the deputies it appears reasonably necessary:\n1. To protect the deputy or other from what reasonably appears to be an immediate threat of death or serious bodily injury; or\n2. To affect the arrest or prevent the escape of a fleeing suspect if the deputy has reasonable cause to believe that the suspect has committed a felony and that the crime for which the suspect is wanted involved the infliction or threatened infliction of serious physical harm, and the suspect reasonably appears to pose a threat of death or serious bodily injury to the deputy or others; or,",
