      "requires_deescalation": 1,
      "policy_language_requires_deescalation": "Yes. \"De-escalation is taking action and/or communicating verbally or non-verbally during a potential force encounter to stabilize the situation and reduce the immediacy of a threat so that more time, options, and resources are available to resolve the situation using the least force necessary. Deescalation is also an effort to reduce or end the use of force after a threat has diminished.\n When reasonable, officers will gather information about the incident, assess the risk, assemble resources, attempt to slow momentum, communicate with the subject, and coordinate a response.\n Officers should use advisements, warnings, verbal persuasion, and other tactics as alternatives to higher levels of force. When feasible, an officer may withdraw to a position that is tactically more secure or allows greater distance in order to consider or deploy a greater variety of force options.",
      "bans_chokeholds_and_strangleholds": 1,
      "policy_language_bans_chokeholds_and_strangleholds": "Yes. \"The use of vascular neck restraint (carotid) or choke holds are prohibited.",
      "duty_to_intervene": 1,
      "policy_language_duty_to_intervene": "Yes.\n A member who observes another member using inappropriate, unnecessary, or unreasonable force shall intervene to stop the use of force when there is a reasonable opportunity to do so. A member who witnesses inappropriate, unnecessary, or unreasonable use of force by another member shall report it as soon as practicable to a supervisor.",
      "requires_warning_before_shooting": 1,
      "policy_language_requires_warning_before_shooting": "Yes. \"Officers shall, whenever possible, identify themselves as police officers and issue a verbal warning prior to using deadly force, unless such identification and warning would jeopardize their safety or the safety of another person.",
      "restricts_shooting_at_moving_vehicles": 1,
      "policy_language_restricts_shooting_at_moving_vehicles": "Yes. \"At a moving vehicle unless deadly force, is being used against the officer or a third party. In such cases, the deadly force shall be directed at the driver or occupant using the deadly force. There is no presumption that a moving vehicle constitutes deadly force. Officers will attempt to use tactics that will not put them in harms way and will make every reasonable effort to move out of the path of a moving vehicle.",
      "requires_comprehensive_reporting": 1,
      "policy_language_requires_comprehensive_reporting": "Yes. Pointing a weapon at a civilian is required to be reported along with other types of force. Threatened use of force through the aiming of a lethal or less-lethal projectile weapon at a person, without firing, or any arcing of an CEW to gain compliance of a subject - Documentation required in Incident\n Report and/or Supplementary Report(s)",
      "requires_exhaust_other_means_before_shooting": 1,
      "policy_language_requires_exhaust_other_means_before_shooting": "Yes. \"Deadly force is authorized when an officer reasonably perceives an imminent threat of serious physical injury or death to the officer or another person. Deadly force is a measure to be employed only in the most extreme circumstances when all lesser means of force have failed or could not be reasonably employed. ",
      "has_use_of_force_continuum": 1,
      "policy_language_has_use_of_force_continuum": "Yes. See Force Model, Levels of Resistance and Levels of Force."
