      "policy_language_requires_warning_before_shooting": "Category: Requires Verbal Warning Before Shooting \nCity Policy: Sheriff's Department Policy Manual \nImpact on Police Violence: Requires officers to give a verbal warning prior to shooting \nPolicy Language: 300.4 DEADLY FORCE APPLICATIONS in regard to shooting a fleeing subject, \"a verbal warning should precede the use of deadly force, where feasible.\" In a scenario in which the officer fears for their life there is no language about providing a verbal warning before shooting.",
      "restricts_shooting_at_moving_vehicles": 0,
      "policy_language_restricts_shooting_at_moving_vehicles": "Category: Bans Shooting at Moving Vehicles\nCity Policy: Sheriff's Department Policy Manual \nImpact on Police Violence: Allows officers to shoot at moving vehicles even when the vehicle itself is considered the only threat. The <a href=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/sep/01/moving-targets-police-shootings-vehicles-the-counted> federal government, activists and even law enforcement groups have recommended that this practice be banned because it endangers lives.\nPolicy Language: 300.4.1 SHOOTING AT OR FROM MOVING VEHICLES Shots fired at or from a moving vehicle are rarely effective. Deputies should move out of the path of an approaching vehicle instead of discharging their firearm at the vehicle or any of its occupants. A deputy should only discharge a firearm at a moving vehicle or its occupants when the deputy reasonably believes there are no other reasonable means available to avert the threat of the vehicle, or if deadly force other than the vehicle is directed at the deputy or others. Deputies should not shoot at any part of a vehicle in an attempt to disable the vehicle.",
      "requires_comprehensive_reporting": 1,
